15 Sep 2012 00:27






We seem to conceal other anomalies of similar scale. Now, whether that's good enough for this article to stand on its own, it's up to you guys.

EDIT: The way I envision it going is that any professional organizations who notice this will have Foundation assets monitoring them for numerous anomalous phenomena, who will then work to conceal it. Amateur astronomers may or may not notice this, since the difference in immediately observable differences is quite small. If they report their findings, sooner or later they will attract the attention of the Foundation, which will contain the knowledge.

It's worth noting that Iapetus already has a highly eccentric orbit in real life, so these changes may be less likely to attract attention anyway.





